<graph edgedefault="undirected"><node id="Article 37">
  <data key="d0">Article 37</data>
  <data key="d1">content</data>
  <data key="d2">Article 37 is a provision in Chinese labor law addressing wage and working hour standards for piece-rate workers.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-db161f575c0e9349bf3b18d1733f159c</data>
  <data key="d4">/Users/pysama/first_prize_RAG/dataset/labor_law.md</data>
  <data key="d5">1773320345</data>
  <data key="d6"></data>
</node>
<node id="Employer">
  <data key="d0">Employer</data>
  <data key="d1">organization</data>
  <data key="d2">The Employer is a legal entity or individual that enters into formal labor contracts with workers, thereby establishing legally governed employment relationships and serving as one of the two principal contracting parties in labor law. As such, the Employer holds managerial authority—including the right to direct work activities, issue instructions, set labor quotas, determine piece-rate remuneration standards (within statutory working hour limits), and terminate contracts under legally defined conditions—provided terminations are accompanied by written notice and justified under applicable labor law. When contracts are rendered invalid due to the Employer’s fault, it bears liability for resulting damages.

The Employer carries extensive statutory obligations across multiple domains. It must pay wages in full and on time, ensuring compensation meets or exceeds the local minimum wage, and determine wage levels and distribution methods in alignment with operational characteristics and economic performance. It is required to compensate employees during statutory leave periods—including holidays, sick leave, maternity leave, and other socially protected absences—and to comply with protections specific to vulnerable groups, such as female and underage workers. The Employer must ensure workers receive at least one day of rest per week, formulate and enforce labor regulations governing working hours and wage payments, and consult with the labor union and affected workers before implementing extended working hours necessitated by operational needs.

Occupational safety and health constitute core responsibilities: the Employer must establish and maintain robust safety and health systems, enforce national regulations and technical standards, supply appropriate protective equipment, provide mandatory safety education, and ensure safe working conditions; failure may trigger legal accountability, including penalties under provisions such as Article 96 for safety violations. Additionally, the Employer is obligated to participate in the national social insurance system and pay required premiums on behalf of employees for pensions, medical care, unemployment, work-related injury, and maternity insurance. It must also engage in equal negotiations with workers—often through representative bodies—to safeguard their lawful rights and interests, improve collective welfare, enhance workers’ welfare benefits, and may establish or engage with labor dispute mediation committees.

Beyond these affirmative duties, the Employer is subject to inspection and regulation by labor administrative departments regarding compliance with labor laws and regulations. It is legally obligated to report and handle workplace accidents and occupational diseases, and to fulfill all contractual terms—including timely payment and provision of adequate working conditions. The Employer bears responsibility for safeguarding commercial secrets and may suffer economic losses due to breaches of contract or confidentiality by workers. Conversely, the Employer itself may violate labor law—for example, by unlawfully terminating employment contracts or deliberately delaying contract signing—thereby incurring legal liability and remedial obligations. Collectively, these roles position the Employer as a central, yet strictly regulated, actor in labor relations—exercising authority only within boundaries defined by law, collective bargaining, and enforceable worker protections.&lt;SEP&gt;An employer is a legal entity or individual that hires workers and is prohibited from employing minors under the age of sixteen, except under specific conditions.&lt;SEP&gt;The employer is the entity that may carry out staff reductions under specific legal conditions, such as imminent bankruptcy or severe operational difficulties.&lt;SEP&gt;An employer is an entity that hires workers and is subject to labor regulations, including prohibitions on hiring minors under sixteen.&lt;SEP&gt;An employer is an entity that hires laborers and is legally restricted from terminating employment contracts under certain protected conditions.&lt;SEP&gt;The Employer is an entity that may obstruct labor administration departments and retaliate against whistleblowers, subject to penalties under labor law.</data>
  <data key="d3">chunk-db161f575c0e9349bf3b18d1733f159c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0f133335b434209fb07a50ad3e0a2f33&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-eb26be1be6719b2d63eda122721b5d68&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9a17dbf9d68b3a46e25ed3308c88ffbf&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fc2cc869b28e0784bd829a72850245ab&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-82eedbfc6978ce7b8284768afbfab33f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-35ee711c6a1d7e90851eb7505f271fc1&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-25702dd54870df07d3bedb29b9496851&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-900f9424a8f6a615634cfe7eb308739e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7440e9a9d68a40eb06fc88eaf48bf3a0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6768f8c1f0e359974ecafdba6b02c7c&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-9ade40507636905dbb256fde347d4c4d&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1c3f29bba2e48ace661e0e106cd6c106&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-11661d5949c7a4c46892595299c2a3db&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e04f20b8b7b250ab2854ffab0ad26c2&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f1e934469e0af82604f570bd7744c5cb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-29625ec97f3aa262c09d4aa1c862291b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-484ec462bb336f0faad2e38a9ab16421&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-73b6c9297c7a7da453da3a92e368350a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f6caf56110d85965c35a028c39252a52&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-add3425ac8339584dcc65694586b9a03&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a07aa9ee7ca74e51c0e67e4531d28af0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1affc2633f7ab17127fc986e6c20944&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f5cd7ed5505461fd7709fa8b54316269&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-15db89e812c6ec17f40e3e2ae7f1d0cd&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2dd1fd3462e1832af7cfde4c6f880f76&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-8bca3d7a5b26e41a901895456edf1d72&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1b224bc392defbea2ebc9ea123f70db&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5a7d21f4dbacb9974d96f6a4b7cd73aa&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6446a7689e729164af31e8ab0faafc8b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b31fb50320a0aa42681462a5892c534&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-01ab560573c5cd878f4442fcbbac6cef&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c1a4ebf44debb9e60481cc178f07fa11&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-4d8030db75e52bd9e7110fb8f615de79&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c6a093f2a713e82a84a2df8dea3ab064&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5f221ff98ea22e9acb2603a0162c0526&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-982fdc171e24d19c2286c2a017fe7f13&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-09d777684aee4aa08ce23008df6295e7&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-49dfcfe749ae5b7a3d964afb5d16559b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-e07869d7cd11d05487d341eeabe67b63&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55fedf8879833ede48386f292722cc7d</data>
  <data key="d4">/Users/pysama/first_prize_RAG/dataset/labor_law.md</data>
